50c Old Indian Eczema Oint\nment 39c\n25c Mykrantz\u2019s Liquid Com\nRemedy 15c\n1.00 Mykrantz\u2019s Sarsaparilla\nand Iron Blood Tonic 69c\n$1.00 La Creole Hair Dressing 83c\n25c Nature\u2019s Remedy (N. R.\nTablets) 19c\n15c Green Mountain Salve __ 11c\nsi.10 Nicotol Nerve Tablets.... 83c\n20c Bouquet dcis Fleurs Talcum 18c\n75c Lower\u2019s Prescription for\nCoughs and Colds ($1.50 size,\n$1.19) 59c\n20c Odorno (60c size, 43c)....... 23c\n20c Seidlitz Powders (box of\n100) 21c\n50c Q-Ban Hair Tonic 39c\n70c Sloan\u2019s Liniment 53c\nFITZSIMMONS BROS. Undertaking Co.\nALL CALLS ANSWERED DAY OR NIGHT\nMrs. Fitzsimmons, Lady A tendant for Women and Children\nAuto Phone 2072 103 E. Main St. Bell Phone OOO-\nThe Leader for Job Work with Both Labels\nTHE NEWARK LEADER\nCDL\u2019RT DECREES\nMO PF STRIKE\nJudge Sisk of Massachusetts\nSuperior Tribunal Makes\nArbitrary Decision.\nUNION ALLOWED NO RIGHTS\nInjunction Is Considered to Be the\nMost Sweeping Ever Handed Down\nin This Country\u2014Affects Shoa\nWorker^\u2019 Organization.\nJudge Sisk of the Massachusetts Su\nperior court ordered an end of the\nstrike xvhich shoe workers of the\nThomas (1. Plant factory, Jamaica\nPlains, began May 13, 1919, in an en\ndeavor to force a closed shop. The in\njunction issued by the court restrains\nall officers and members of the unions\naffected from continuing, supporting\nor encouraging the strike or any new\nstrike called for the same purpose.\nThe decree, which is sweeping and\nperpetual, takes up in detail all pos\nsible strike activities. Under its pro\nvisions the unions will not be allowed\nto pay any further strike benefits or to\npicket, Intimidate employees or en\ndeavor to induce them to abandon their\nemployment.\nThey are also forbidden to represent\nthe company as unfair to union labor\nor try to prevail on other business\nhouses not to deal with the company.\nCommenting on the decision, the\nPhiladelphia Public Ledger says: \u201cA\nMassachusetts court has just made one\nof the most sweeping orders in re\nstraint of organized labor to be found\nin the annals of industrial litigation in\nthis country. There is hardly anything\nopen to organized labor in the way of\nprosecuting a dispute that is not for\nbidden in this drastic order.\u201d\nGENERAL LABOR NEWS\nPhiladelphia manufactures 211 of\nthe 264 products made in America.\nThe largest steel plant in tlie Ori\nent has just been completed at Yawa\nta. Japan.\nPractically 75 per cent of the tex\ntile mills in Philadelphia are closed\ndown indefinitely.\nOver $5,000,000 was paid out in\nMassachusetts last year under the\nworkmen\u2019s compensation law.\nAt a meeting of the Georgia-Florida\nSawmill association it was decided\nthat wages would be cut 25 per cent\nat once.\nNinety-nine per cent of the em\nployees of the Liberty Motor com\npany at Detroit, Mich., are American\ncitizens.\nA recent survey made by the local\nauthorities in England and Wales\nshows the urgent need of 795,000\nhouses.\n4 Stove mounters in Richmond, Va\u201e\nhave reorganized their local and are\naffiliated with the Stove Mounters\u2019 In\nternational union.\nIn Germany some leather is being\nmade from waste leather, which is\nsuitable for the manufacture of heels\nfor shoes of all kinds.\nMore than 500,000 women are still\nemployed in the shops throughout the\nUnited States, very few having quit\ntheir jobs at the termination of the\nwar.\nStriking stevedores and dock work\ners in Vera Cruz, Mex., refused to ac\ncept the agreement reached at Mexico\nCity by representatives of the cham\nbers of commerce and industry and\nthe Shipowners\u2019 association with Pro\nvisional President de la Huerta. They\nIssued a call for a general strike.\nThree hundred and twenty men\nwere killed in tlie mining industry in\nWest Virginia during the year ended\nJune 30 last, according to the annual\nreport of the state department of\nmines. The report shows that fatal\naccidents during the year decreased\nby 55 from the total during a corre\nsponding period of the year previous.\nJudge Jacob Moses, chairman for\nthe settlement of the disputes be\ntween the Amalgamated Clothing\nWorkers and the manufacturers, gave\na decision which is expected to have\na far-reaching effect on the clothing\nindustry. It recognizes the obligation\nupon the worker to co-operate with\nthe manufacturer in efforts to in\ncrease production, even when such\nco-operation means fewer days of em\nployment in tlie week for the em\nployee.\nTne plant of the Hodges Fiber Car\nnet company, Springfield. Mass., is\nclosed following the refusal of the\n350 employees to accept a cut of 15\nper cent in wages which the manage\nment says Is the only way the plant\ncan be kept In operation. W. F.\nHodges, superintendent, said the fac\ntory would remain closed until orders\nwarranted paying the old wages.\nMembers of the Loom Fixers\u2019 union\nvoted to support the textile workers.\nA wage reduction of 10 per cent be\ncame effective in all cotton mills in\nthe vicinity of Union, S. C., affecting\napproximately 3,000 employees. The\nmills will be closed two days a week\nalso. The cotton market situation was\ngiven as the reason for the curtail\nment\nThe passage of a city of 100,000 in\nhabitants from the exclusive employ\nment of union labor to an entire open\nshop program is claimed to have been\naccorrqilished at Shreveport, La., vyith\nout a walkout, a strike, or any kind\nof trouble, in October.\nStriking compositors on tlie Tokyo\n(Japan) newspapers wreaked ven\ngeance on the paper that is leading\nthe opposition to their demands far\nan eight-hour day. They \u201cpied\u201d the\ntype, eqch font of which consists of\nmore than 3,000 different Chinese\nhieroglyphics and 75 Japanese char\nacters.\nIn a comprehensive report on em\nployment, wages, cost of living and\nmarket conditions, made public by\nthe Mtrchants\u2019 association, experts\nassorted that there was no sign of\ngeneral business depression, but that\nwholesale prices would have to be cut\nat least 50 per cent before they ap\nproximated the prewar level. The re\nport says that some industries have\nreported a larger number of em\nployees for the last few months.\nA general strike of 2.000 grocery\nclerks in 900 Washington grocery\nstores of the city has begun. Harry\nBloomfield, secretary of the Retail\nGrocery Clerks\u2019 union, in announc\ning the general strike, said that the\ndemands of the men are for an in\ncrease of $6 a week, thus raising the\nwages of the grocery clerks to $35 a\nweek for first grade clerks, $30 a\nweek for second class clerks and $25\na week for apprentices. A 57-hour\nweek is also asked.\nFour hours\u2019 extra work or less pay\nIs the ultimatum that has been hand\ned to the 3.500 employees of Julius\nKayser Company, New York, silk\nmerchants. The firm has a 44-hour\nweek in operation since the war. Now\nit announces the resumption of the\n48-hour week.\nRailway clerks, freight handlers\nand station employees of the Cana\ndian Pacific railway, western lines,\nhave negotiated wage increases that\naverage $25 a month. The award\ndates back to May 1\nOFF\nHouse Coats\nBath Robes\nTraveling Bags\nToilet Sets\nMilitary Brushes\nManicure Sets\nHandkerchiefs\nKhaki Kerchiefs\nV Neck Sweaters\nV Neck Jerseys\nSweater Coats\nSilk Pajamas\nS Give \u201cHIM\u201d A Union Label\ni-SUITorOVERCOA\nWE CAN GIVE YOU\nHIS CORRECT SIZE\nThe best Christmas present you can make\nto each member of your family would be\nto start a savings account at\nThe Licking County Building Savings Co.\n34 North Third Street, Opposite Arcade\nAT 5X INTEREST\nIT TEACHES THRIFT AND ECONOMY\nGifts From Here Make the Best Showing\nHoliday Hints\n\u201cGifts From the Hub Are Sure to Please\u201d\nOuting Pajamas\nMuslin Pajamas\nSilk Shirts\nFlannel Shirts\nMadras Shirts\nUmbrellas\nFancy Silk Socks\nSilk Mufflers\nSilk Neckwear\nKid Gloves\nMocha _Gloves\nWool Gloves\nSilk Gloves\nLined Gloves\nGifts For The Boys\nRaincoats